    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1905-06-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1905-06-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="793"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d793">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">Meyer</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">St. Petersburg</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1905-06-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 29, 1905</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 89.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I beg leave to report that on the 22d and 23d of
                    June there was a strike of all the workmen in the mills and factories in the
                    city of Lodz. Many wine shops were totally demolished, and frequent conflicts
                    occurred between the strikers and the troops, which consisted of regiments of
                    infantry and cavalry. The disturbances looked so serious that I cabled to the
                    Department, true reading of which is as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Serious disturbances at Lodz Friday between 60,000 workmen and troops,
                            four regiments of infantry; two cavalry took part; many streets
                            barricaded; nothing authentic as to number of killed and wounded. Alarm
                            felt in Warsaw; workmen striking; crowds assembling.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>The latest reports now state that the city has recovered almost its normal
                    condition and workmen are gradually returning to their duties.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">G. v. L. Meyer</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
